---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="About the numbers · Carbon Plate">
  <main class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-5 py-10 prose prose-navy">
    <a href="/" class="handwritten text-peach-500">← back to the plate</a>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold mt-2">about the numbers</h1>
    <p class="handwritten text-xl text-peach-500">a.k.a. the small print, written kindly</p>

    <p>
      Carbon Plate uses a hand-curated table of <strong>~30 food carbon coefficients</strong>
      in kg CO₂-equivalent per 100g of edible food. We pulled them from
      Poore &amp; Nemecek (2018), Our World in Data, and ADEME's Agribalyse database,
      then averaged where they disagreed.
    </p>

    <p>
      These are <em>cradle-to-fork-ish</em> estimates. They smooth out a huge amount of
      variability — your local farmer's chicken is not the global mean chicken, your
      grandma's beef-Wellington is not industrial beef, etc. Treat the result as a
      vibe check, not an audit.
    </p>

    <h2>ocean equivalents</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>phytoplankton m²</strong> — phytoplankton fix roughly
        50 g of carbon per m² per year (≈ 183 g CO₂). So 1 kg CO₂ needs about
        5.46 m² working all year to undo it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>km driven</strong> — assumes an average passenger car at 0.17
        kg CO₂ per km (EU fleet average).
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>privacy</h2>
    <p>
      Your photos are sent to Anthropic's Claude API for analysis (or skipped entirely
      in demo mode). Streaks are stored in <code>localStorage</code> on your device.
      We don't run a database. We don't have analytics. We don't have your inbox.
    </p>

    <p class="handwritten text-lg text-peach-500">
      built in 36 hours by two people who eat too much steak.
    </p>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
